===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# On a [[clock]] or [[watch]], the [[hand]] or [[pointer]] that shows the number of [[second]]s that have passed.
# An intermediate person or means; [[intermediary]].
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Memoirs of Jonathan Swift, D.D., Dean of St Patrick's, Dublin| page=135| url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1108034187| editor={{w|Walter Scott}}| passage=“My Lord Oxford, by a '''second hand''', proposed my being his chaplain, which I, by a '''second hand''', excused.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=The Magdalen, and other tales| page=3| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i6cBAAAAQAAJ| author=James Sheridan Knowles| year=1832| passage=Under certain circumstances there is always a danger in a young man's playing the benefactor towards the other sex, in his own person. A thousand times better do it by a '''second hand''' — engage the services of some kind aunt or female cousin.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=A Land of Strangers: Cane Creek Tennessee's Mormon Massacre and its Tragic Effects on the People Who Lived There| url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1304275590| author=Bruce Crow| year=2013| passage=So nearly every name comes from a '''second hand''' source. The exception to this rule has been the vigilantes themselves. Rube Mathis and Jack Wells, both admitted to participating, and Mathis identified his brother.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Life in Words: Essays on Chaucer, the Gawain-Poet, and Malory| url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=144261742X| author=Jill Mann| year=2014| passage=The relation of Tristram's death is thus distanced from the narrative to which it belongs, and it is also distanced in that we do not see it happen with our own eyes, but hear of it by a '''second-hand''' report which introduces it incidentally, not for its own sake.}}

